06913nam a22008055i 9780226660295DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20192019ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019012198  a9780226660295  a(DE-B1597)535502  a(OCoLC)1129235877  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHF5415.1b.L64 2019 4aHF5415.1b.L64 2020 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a381.089090732231 aLogemann, Jan L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEngineered to Sell :bEuropean Émigrés and the Making of Consumer Capitalism /cJan L. Logemann. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b21 halftones, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Consumer Engineers and the Transnational Origins of Consumer Capitalism -- t1. The Origins of “Consumer Engineering”: Interwar Consumer Capitalism in Transatlantic Perspective -- tSection One. Transformations in Marketing and Consumer Research -- tThe Rise of Consumer Engineering: American Marketing at Midcentury (1930s–1960s) -- t2. The Art of Asking Why: The “Vienna School” of Market Research and Transfers in Consumer Psychology -- t3. From Mass Persuasion to Engineered Consent: The Impact of “European” Psychology on the Cognitive Turn in Marketing Thought -- t4 Hidden Persuaders? Market Researchers as “Knowledge Entrepreneurs” between Business and the Social Sciences -- tSection Two. Designing for Sustained Demand -- t“Tastemakers” or “Wastemakers”? Commercial Design at Midcentury (1930–1960) -- t5. The Designer as Marketing Expert: European Immigrants and the Professionalization of Industrial and Graphic Design in the United States -- t6. The Commercialization of Social Engineering? Adapting Radical Design Reform to American Mass Marketing -- t7. “Streamlining Everything”: Design, Market Research, and the Postwar “American” World of Goods -- tSection Three. Transatlantic Return Voyages -- tBridging Transatlantic Divides: Bringing Consumer Modernity “Back” to Europe -- t8. Corporate America and the International Style: The Transnational Network of Knoll Associates between Europe and the United States -- t9. The “Return” to Europe: Emigrés as Cultural Translators and the Transformation of Postwar European Marketing -- tConsumer Engineering: Challenges and Legacies -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations for Archival Sources -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aForever immortalized in the television series Mad Men, the mid-twentieth century marketing world influenced nearly every aspect of American culture—music, literature, politics, economics, consumerism, race relations, gender, and more. In Engineered to Sell, Jan Logemann traces the transnational careers of consumer engineers in advertising, market research and commercial design who transformed capitalism, from the 1930s through the 1960s. He argues that the history of marketing consumer goods is not a story of American exceptionalism. Instead, the careers of immigrants point to the limits of the “Americanization” paradigm. First, Logemann explains the rise of a dynamic world of goods by emphasizing changes in marketing approaches increasingly tailored to consumers. Second, he looks at how and why consumer engineering was shaped by transatlantic exchanges. From Austrian psychologists and little-known social scientists to the illustrious Bauhaus artists, the émigrés at the center of this story illustrate the vibrant cultural and commercial connections between metropolitan centers: Vienna and New York; Paris and Chicago; Berlin and San Francisco. These mid-century consumer engineers crossed national and disciplinary boundaries not only within arts and academia but also between governments, corporate actors, and social reform movements. By focusing on the transnational lives of émigré consumer researchers, marketers, and designers, Engineered to Sell details the processes of cultural translation and adaptation that mark both the mid-century transformation of American marketing and the subsequent European shift to “American” consumer capitalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aConsumerszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aConsumerszUnited States. 0aImmigrantszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrantszUnited States. 0aIndustrial designxHistoryy20th century. 0aMarketingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMarketingzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMarketing-United States-History. 0aNew productsxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aBusiness History, Consumer History.  aDesign History.  aElite Migration.  aEmigration.  aHistory of Capitalism.  aKnowledge transfers.  aMarketing History.  aTransatlantic Relations.  aTransnational History.  aWesternization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019z9783110606195oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311071194340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226660295423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226660295/original  a978-3-11-061017-8  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-071194-3  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019